title: For Sale:  Used Feather AT-9 carbine in 9mm with 4 Pre-ban Mags.
postcontent:
Up for sale is a used Feather Industries AT-9 carbine. The rifle is in post ban configuration with removable wire stock. It was designed to use slightly modified UZI magazines. There is a small notch cut into a standard UZI mag, which is very easy to duplicate. An interesting feature of this rifle is that it was intentionally made to break down allow it to be stored in a compact space. Great camping or back pack rifle. It would also make a really cool SBR project if you want to get a tax stamp and cut the barrel down.
     I've heard and read a lot of great things about these cool little carbines and they have a reputation for being extremely accurate for what they are. I haven't tested it myself. Check out the beefy thick barrel.
     The rifle comes with 4 mags total. One 20-round Feather factory magazine that could use a new follower, one pre ban uzi mag that it looks like someone altered at home, it actually fits and feeds very well. Plus two unaltered pre ban UZI mags that haven't been notched yet. You can do it yourself if you're even remotely handy, or just bring them to a gunsmith and have it done professionally.

The gun is being sold AS IS. The lower price reflects that.
I have never fired it or bothered to take it to the range because I noticed that it has a problem extracting a round from the chamber. It's a very tight fit and you have to pull the round out by hand, this could probably easily be solved by reaming the chamber, an easy fix any competent gunsmith can do for a reasonable price. The condition of the weapon is good used. It has a good shiny bore, but has the usual little scratches and imperfections from range use. It's not a safe queen. The price listed is very fair for it's condition and what it is. I'd like to see this stay in mass versus listing it on an auction site, but if nobody bites I'll just list it on gunbroker. 

These are still being made by a company called FeatherUSA and parts are available. 

Not interested in trades unless you have something thats rare and interesting. (Hard to find non mass compliant handguns, antiques, and collectible firearms) your Ruger, Smith M&P or 3rd gen Glock that grows on trees isn't rare.

I have had this one sitting in my gun safe for a while and am looking to sell some project guns I don't have time to finish, as well as free up some space in the safe. This isn't a fire sale so don't waste either of our time with low ball offers. 

Sale will be face to face,  and transfer will be done at local FFL dealer. Transfer fee will be paid by the buyer.

location: South Dakota, South Dakota, United States
postcontent: NO RESERVE!! Here's one of the "Holy Grails" for the WWII military arms collector. This is a U.S. Marine Corps M1903A1 Sniper Rifle. Sometimes called the M1941 Sniper Rifle, this weapon was developed early in WWII and combined an accurized M1903A1 National Match rifle with a J. Unertl 8x rifle scope. This initial production utilized the metal components of 1047 National Match rifles that had been segregated in USMC Rifle Team stores.

This gun looks and feels like the real thing and is of the correct size and weight and having original Tomphson wood with the sling swivels and metal butt plate with the door for the cleaning rod. It is made up with a Ruger 10-22 action. The 10-22 receiver has been mounted inside a full size copy of a Tomphson receiver and the bolt handle has been removed and been replaced with a top operating stud like the originals. The gun was produced by Attica Forge of Lapeer Michigan. The gun functions flawlessly and has a Lyman ladder peep rear sight. A very rare and  impressive gun  that I have been unable to find any information on. $600.00 or reasonable offer.

title: For Sale:  M1 Garand .30 Caliber Sprigfield Armory. NM(Type-1)
postcontent:
For Sale: M1 Garand Springfield Armory M1 Rifle NM-1 (Type-1) SN: 5809XXX dated: 2-55

(Information below was taken from an NRA article on NM Garand's. I added a few “added notes” as to this Rifle for your information.)
Between 1953-1955 Springfield Armory produced the first of the NM series rifles the NM-1 (Type-1), serial numbers will be between approximately 5,800,000 and 6,100,000. 
Most of the unaltered original Type 1 NM rifles will exhibit the following characteristics
-Markings on right receiver leg: Drawing number, “6528287-SA;” Heat Lot, T 1 to T 10 - Z 5 to Z15 (added note: This Rifle receiver drawing no: F6528291 Heat lot; Z6A, Which matches Springfield Armory records for NM receiver. Left side receiver is stamped with "S")
-Barrel: Marked “T” for (targeted); “P” for (proofed); “SA F6535448” (Add Note: This Barrel is marked "SA F 6525448 drawing number with two "S" stamps over the F); Month and year of barrel production; Heat lot code, “m” (magnetic particle testing) and Defense Acceptance Stamp (Added Note: This Rifle has additional inverted "P" with punch mark center "P" loop which was used as early NM marking).
-Bolt: “6522887-SA” (with heat lot code) (Added Note: This rifle Bolt "6528287-SA)
-Windage Knob: “DRC”
-Elevation Knob: “WCE” (Added Note: This rifle has "DRC" Elevation Knob)
""It should be noted that the early production examples (1953-1955) may have different parts from those listed above."" Stocks for NM-1 Rifles were not glassed, but rather hand selected for tight fit and uniform wood grain.
Springfield Armory engineers and armors worked closely to prefect the Nation Match 1 rifle.  
The exact number of Type 1 National Match rifles made is unknown. There is a much-published chart purporting to give a breakdown of M1 National Match production from 1953 to 1963. 

This is a rare find for the shooters or collector. NM-1's are rare in this condition.

Note: Buyer Pays: Shipping and DOJ registration fees
I will consider reasonable offers. 

This is a nice accurate shooting rifle in excellent condition and all the marking as stated above.. For Shooter or Collector. Rare find!
Please, contact me with any other questions you may have about this M1 Garand.
